<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-634-058  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 634 058.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  June 6 1990 n1511 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A telephone call away from solving the crime. (obscene calls andthe technology to detect them)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In Britain, computer hackers are detected through the use of thetelephone system.andP;  While the detection of computer hackers takespriority over the detection of nuisance callers, it is not carriedout without trouble.andP;  New legislation in the form of the ComputerMisuse Bill promises to deal with these problems.andP;  Britain couldlook to the States, however, for means in which to detect nuisancecallers.andP;  For example, Bell Atlantic in New Jersey, unlike BritishTelecom which must wait for a police request before tracing acall, has developed Caller ID, a system operating via digitalsignals.andP;  Caller ID allows receivers to access the telephonenumbers of nuisance callers.andP;  Although Caller ID has been declaredillegal by some state regulatory commissions, in general, it hasbeen a successful system, and Bell Atlantic has succeeded insolving some of the problems inherent to any call tracing system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Atlantic Corp. (communication systems)British Telecommunications PLC (communication systems).andO;Ticker:    BEL.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsTelephone SystemsDigital SignalsComputer CrimesLegislation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>